A yearly subscription is refundable within 14 days of purchase and includes a 365-day membership. The South African petrochemicals company also said it had reached an agreement with its lenders on covenant amendment for December 31 and that the covenant for June 2021 will remain at 3x net debt: earnings before interest, taxation, depreciation and amortisation. Investors have been concerned by the company’s debt, which has been exacerbated by delays and cost overruns at its Lake Charles Chemicals project (LCCP) in Louisiana and prompted the resignations of its joint chief executives to restore shareholder confidence. Sasol’s total debt was R189.7 billion for the year to June 30. Turnaround Also on Wednesday, Sasol said it aims to reduce annual capital expenditure by 30% over next three to four years, as part of a turnaround strategy. Sasol also aims to cut fixed costs and lift gross margins. “We need to transform the business so that it is highly cash generative, with a diversified assets base that yields competitive returns to our shareholders through commodity cycles and market volatility,” said chief financial officer Paul Victor.